{
  "answer": "In *Tarana-e-Milli*, the principle of belonging to a single *millat* (Muslim *ummah*)—transcending all lands—is most starkly stated in the opening couplet: \"From Chin to Arab lands, our story flows, / The whole wide world's the home a Muslim knows.\"[^1]\n\nIn *Manusmṛti* Book 1, the principle of humans being distributed into fixed *varnas* (social orders) at the moment of creation is most starkly stated as: \"he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.\"[^2]\n\nThese forms of belonging exclude each other. The *millat* is a voluntary, egalitarian bond of faith open to all Muslims regardless of birth or geography, whereas *varna* is an involuntary, hierarchical assignment by cosmic origin and heredity, confined to a specific Indic order of *dharma*.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Tarana-e-Milli\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-8a4681).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).",
